    "ocr_text": "X.
APR. 6, 1910.
Mr. A. N. Burbank, President,
International Paper Company,
30 Broad Street, New York City.
Dear Sir:
Having received information as to the unsatisfactory relations between your Company and the men employed in the paper mills making industry, in discussing general matters affecting the interests of the wage earners of the country, the Executive Council of the A. F. of L. at its recent meeting also discussed the trouble existing between the paper makers and your company and the desire was expressed by the Executive Council that every effort should be made to establish better relations between the management of the company and the representatives of organized labor.
I am writing therefore to inquire whether a conference could not be arranged between a representative of the A. F. of L. and representatives of the organizations of the men working in the paper industry for the purpose of discussing these questions of difference, with the hope of reaching some basis of agreement whereby a sub-committee from such conference may be authorized to wait upon you and your fellow officers so as to present to you such suggested basis of agreement. I trust that this suggestion may meet with your sympathy and that I may be favored with an early reply.
Very truly yours,
",
